[
  {
    "label": "Same contract, opposite outcome",
    "ids": [
      "termination-trap",
      "rag"
    ],
    "desc": "Both conditional permission. Training exits entangled; RAG exits clean.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Permission",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Same legal gate",
        "commentary": "Both stances start from conditional permission, so the contractual trigger is not the differentiator. The outcome changes because the technical processing path changes what termination can actually unwind."
      },
      {
        "row": "Processing Mode",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Training versus inference",
        "commentary": "Training embeds licensed material into model behavior, while inference-time retrieval keeps the data externally separable. This row explains why the same licence can produce opposite exit outcomes."
      },
      {
        "row": "Retention / Persistence",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Entangled or ephemeral",
        "commentary": "Weight-entangled use makes the data relationship persist after access is revoked. Ephemeral RAG use keeps custody closer to a disconnectable service dependency."
      },
      {
        "row": "Exit",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Exit quality diverges",
        "commentary": "The training case marks exit as entangled, making termination operationally incomplete. The RAG case is clean because removing retrieval access removes the practical use channel."
      },
      {
        "row": "Derivation",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Capability survives",
        "commentary": "Surviving capability is the core harm in the termination gap: the contract ends but the trained system keeps the benefit. RAG has no residual capability because the source is not absorbed into weights."
      },
      {
        "row": "Model-Weight Rights",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Hosted is insufficient",
        "commentary": "Both arrangements say hosted only, but that common legal posture does not settle reversibility. The important distinction is whether value has moved into the hosted model rather than where the model is held."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "Both arrangements use conditional licensed data with declared audit rights, verifiable provenance, hosted-only weights, and allocated liability.",
      "different": "The training path is frontier, multi-domain, weight-entangled, copyable, and locked-in, while RAG is narrow, single-domain, ephemeral, sandboxed, replaceable, and exits cleanly.",
      "impact": "The same permission structure produces opposite remedies because inference-time custody can be disconnected but trained capability survives as residual model value."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "Compliance without observability",
    "ids": [
      "land-grab",
      "audit-illusion"
    ],
    "desc": "Moving from opaque to declared control does not change economics unless observability becomes real.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Declared is not observed",
        "commentary": "The comparison moves from opaque to declared controls, but declared observability still depends on what can actually be inspected. That is why the compliance layer may improve paperwork without changing leverage."
      },
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "Audit remains opaque",
        "commentary": "Verification Gap has conditional licensing and declared provenance, yet the control or audit right remains opaque. This row exposes the gap between compliance form and usable verification."
      },
      {
        "row": "Input Price",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Economics unchanged",
        "commentary": "Both stances keep fixed input pricing, so the shift to compliance language does not alter the economic bargain. The processor can still capture upside without repricing the underlying contribution."
      },
      {
        "row": "Derived Value Capture",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Processor still captures",
        "commentary": "The value capture pattern is identical: derived value remains with the processor. This is the clearest sign that compliance structure alone does not alter the allocation of AI upside."
      },
      {
        "row": "Provenance",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Source story improves",
        "commentary": "Verification Gap upgrades provenance from unknown to declared, which is meaningful for recordkeeping. It is not enough by itself because declared source lineage does not prove downstream control."
      },
      {
        "row": "Risk Allocation / Backstop",
        "type": "note",
        "title": "Risk pushed away",
        "commentary": "The audit case adds disclaimed liability, making the compliance posture look safer while preserving one-sided risk allocation. That makes the declared regime weaker than it appears."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "Both stances keep frontier, multi-domain capability in a closed hosted model where outputs are monitored and processor-side value capture remains intact.",
      "different": "Status Quo is openly permissive and opaque with scraped data and unknown provenance, while Verification Gap adds conditional licensing, declared provenance, benchmarking, and escalation but leaves the audit right opaque.",
      "impact": "Compliance paperwork changes the label of governance without changing control or economics when observability still cannot verify use, derivation, or retained value."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "Different path, same trap",
    "ids": [
      "termination-trap",
      "cross-border"
    ],
    "desc": "Training entanglement and jurisdictional complexity can both converge on the same exit problem.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Exit",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Same exit failure",
        "commentary": "Both paths end in entangled exit even though the causal mechanisms differ. The comparison's point is that technical absorption and cross-border dependency can converge on the same practical trap."
      },
      {
        "row": "Processing Mode",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Different route in",
        "commentary": "Termination gap reaches entanglement through training, while Cross-border Knot does it through adaptation and fine-tuning. The shared outcome is not tied to a single processing mode."
      },
      {
        "row": "Territory",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Domestic versus cross-border",
        "commentary": "The termination case is domestic, so the problem is mainly technical and contractual. The cross-border case adds territory as a source of enforcement and coordination friction."
      },
      {
        "row": "Supply Jurisdiction",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Law fits less cleanly",
        "commentary": "A favorable domestic fit becomes ambiguous in the cross-border knot. That ambiguity can make even declared rights harder to execute when exit is needed."
      },
      {
        "row": "Supply Jurisdiction",
        "type": "note",
        "title": "Exposed supply chain",
        "commentary": "Cross-border Knot adds adversary or exposed supply jurisdiction, turning supplier location into a strategic risk. This creates lock-in even without the same weight-transfer story."
      },
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Rights are declared",
        "commentary": "Both cases claim declared audit or control rights, but both still fail to deliver clean exit. The row shows that formal rights are not enough when the operating architecture resists reversal."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "Both scenarios combine conditional licensed data, declared audit rights, verifiable provenance, frontier multi-domain capability, persistent memory, many copies, and entangled exit.",
      "different": "Termination gap reaches lock-in through domestic training, weight transfer, copyable weights, and claimed derivatives, while Cross-border knot reaches it through distributed residency, ambiguous jurisdiction, committed capacity, and exposed supply jurisdiction.",
      "impact": "Exit failure is not only a model-weight problem; legal geography and infrastructure commitments can reproduce the same entanglement even when rights are better allocated."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "Three sovereign plays",
    "ids": [
      "sov-build",
      "sov-gap",
      "sov-invest"
    ],
    "desc": "Sovereign Build, Sovereign Gap, and Sovereign Stake are distinct signatures.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Capability Class",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Strategic stakes",
        "commentary": "All three sovereign plays sit at the strategic capability level. The differences are therefore about control model and infrastructure posture, not about whether the capability matters."
      },
      {
        "row": "Command Actor",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "State command is uneven",
        "commentary": "Sovereign Build and Sovereign Stake have an explicit state or coalition command actor, while Sovereign Gap lacks that command row. The gap case is sovereign-sensitive without full sovereign direction."
      },
      {
        "row": "Capability Trajectory",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Race versus scale",
        "commentary": "Sovereign Build is marked as an OOM race, while Sovereign Stake is scaling. That separates emergency national buildout from a slower capital-backed infrastructure strategy."
      },
      {
        "row": "Physical Infrastructure",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Industrial build or cloud",
        "commentary": "Only Sovereign Build requires a national industrial build; the other two still sit on commercial cloud. This row cleanly distinguishes true infrastructure sovereignty from cloud-based sovereign posture."
      },
      {
        "row": "Physical Infrastructure",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Power becomes strategy",
        "commentary": "Sovereign Build depends on new generation or grid build, making energy part of the AI strategy. Sovereign Gap and Sovereign Stake use existing power, so they avoid that bottleneck but accept less industrial depth."
      },
      {
        "row": "Input Price",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Pricing reveals posture",
        "commentary": "Sovereign Gap uses fixed pricing, while Sovereign Stake uses structural pricing. The investment model treats AI capacity as infrastructure participation rather than a procurement line item."
      },
      {
        "row": "Boundary",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Sovereign isolation",
        "commentary": "All three mark the boundary as isolated, showing a shared desire to separate the system from ordinary commercial exposure. The strength of that isolation depends on the infrastructure rows around it."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "All three sovereign plays use conditional licensed data, verifiable provenance, hosted-only closed weights, sovereign or extraterritorial residency, retained entanglement, and strategic capability.",
      "different": "Sovereign Build hardens control through owned infrastructure, SCIF isolation, national command, and new power; Sovereign Gap depends on commercial cloud and API distribution; Sovereign Stake buys strategic control through owned compute, captive cloud, and national-security governance.",
      "impact": "The comparison separates sovereignty as operational control, sovereignty as residual exposure, and sovereignty as capital allocation, which require different risk and procurement terms."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "Finance meets architecture",
    "ids": [
      "lifecycle",
      "collateral"
    ],
    "desc": "Tenure fracture is the risk; collateralisation is the opportunity.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Capital",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Project or security",
        "commentary": "Tenure Fracture treats capital as a project, while Data Lien makes it securitised. That is the pivot from architecture risk to financeable asset."
      },
      {
        "row": "Commitment Tenor",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Tenor mismatch",
        "commentary": "Infrastructure-life commitments create long technical exposure, while multi-year collateral terms are shorter and more finance-shaped. The mismatch matters because AI assets may change faster than the financing horizon."
      },
      {
        "row": "Exit",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Collateral needs reversibility",
        "commentary": "Tenure Fracture is entangled, but Data Lien is transitional. Financeability improves when exit can be staged rather than trapped inside a technical architecture."
      },
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Bankable visibility",
        "commentary": "Collateralisation upgrades declared observability to observable operation. That makes monitoring evidence part of the asset package rather than a contractual assertion."
      },
      {
        "row": "Evaluation",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Certification matters",
        "commentary": "Benchmarked evaluation may support engineering confidence, but certified decision-grade evaluation supports underwriting and risk transfer. This row marks the shift from operating metric to finance control."
      },
      {
        "row": "Physical Infrastructure",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Same hard asset base",
        "commentary": "Both stances rely on dedicated clusters, so the opportunity and risk are grounded in the same physical architecture. The financial difference comes from governance and reversibility, not from a different substrate."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "Both models finance committed capacity around licensed data, declared audit rights, verifiable provenance, dedicated clusters, procured power, persistent memory, retained entanglement, and many replicated copies.",
      "different": "Tenure Fracture is an infrastructure-life project with entangled exit and surviving capability, while Data Lien turns the same architecture into securitised, multi-year product-line exposure with certified evaluation and limited warranty.",
      "impact": "Once data and compute become financeable assets, technical reversibility and residual capability determine credit risk as much as contract price or capacity commitment."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "Three pricing models",
    "ids": [
      "recursive",
      "collateral",
      "sov-invest"
    ],
    "desc": "Variable, fixed, and structural pricing each solve one problem and create another.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Input Price",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Three price logics",
        "commentary": "Recursive Pricing is variable, Data Lien is fixed, and Sovereign Stake is structural. This row is the comparison's core taxonomy."
      },
      {
        "row": "Derived Value Capture",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Upside allocation",
        "commentary": "Recursive Pricing leaves derived value with the processor, while Data Lien does not define value capture through that row. The absence matters because fixed pricing can miss compounding upside unless paired with collateral or revenue terms."
      },
      {
        "row": "Capital",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Finance form changes",
        "commentary": "Data Lien is securitised, while Sovereign Stake is a project. Fixed pricing becomes financeable cash flow; structural pricing becomes public or strategic infrastructure participation."
      },
      {
        "row": "Processing Mode",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Use drives price",
        "commentary": "Recursive Pricing is tied to training, while the other two sit in adaptation or fine-tuning. Pricing has to follow the technical mode because value compounds differently when outputs feed future generations."
      },
      {
        "row": "Retention / Persistence",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "All retain something",
        "commentary": "The three models differ in pricing, but none is purely ephemeral: they are weight-entangled or retained. That persistence is why every pricing model needs an answer for downstream value."
      },
      {
        "row": "Output Allocation",
        "type": "note",
        "title": "Structural public upside",
        "commentary": "Only Sovereign Stake adds public or international benefit sharing. Structural pricing is therefore not just a fee model; it encodes a political claim on the upside."
      },
      {
        "row": "Revenue Dependency",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Product revenue link",
        "commentary": "Recursive Pricing and Data Lien both depend on product-line revenue. That common link makes them commercially legible even though one prices variable use and the other packages fixed commitments."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "All three price licensed data into closed hosted systems with conditional permission, verifiable provenance, shared outputs, persistent memory, derived outputs, controlled residency, and retained entanglement.",
      "different": "Recursive Pricing prices compounding training and claimed recursive derivation with variable inputs, Data Lien fixes price through securitised committed capacity, and Sovereign Stake treats price as structural project capital under national command.",
      "impact": "The pricing model determines who absorbs acceleration, asset, and sovereignty risk, so identical data rights can imply very different upside capture and exit exposure."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "Three jurisdictions",
    "ids": [
      "usa",
      "eu",
      "uk"
    ],
    "desc": "US default, EU governance, UK middle path.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Regulatory Posture",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Three legal defaults",
        "commentary": "The US permissive posture treats training as a market default, the EU makes use conditional, and the UK is coded as prohibitive. That makes the comparison primarily about default entitlement rather than technical capability."
      },
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Audit depth separates the models",
        "commentary": "The US remains opaque, the EU is observable, and the UK is only declared. The EU therefore converts rights language into inspection capacity more directly than either the US or UK."
      },
      {
        "row": "Territory",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "EU reach travels outward",
        "commentary": "The EU's extraterritorial setting contrasts with domestic US and UK framing. That gives the EU model leverage over cross-border supply chains, while the others depend more on local market and contract structure."
      },
      {
        "row": "Cloud Dependency",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Infrastructure follows governance",
        "commentary": "EU portability supports its governance posture, while US and UK preferred-partner cloud dependencies keep operational power concentrated. The UK therefore diverges legally from the US but remains close to it infrastructurally."
      },
      {
        "row": "Capability Class",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Same frontier object",
        "commentary": "All three are comparing frontier, multi-domain systems. The policy split is not caused by different capability levels; it is caused by different answers to who may train, observe, control, and retain value."
      },
      {
        "row": "Output Allocation",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "Value allocation remains uneven",
        "commentary": "The US retains private capture, the EU moves to contractual sharing, and the UK leaves benefit sharing less explicit in the picks. Rights protection does not automatically settle who receives the upside."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "All three compare frontier, multi-domain systems, so the split is about entitlement, audit, infrastructure, and value allocation rather than capability level.",
      "different": "The US treats training as permissive and opaque, the EU makes it conditional, observable, extraterritorial, and portable, and the UK is more prohibitive on rights but remains closer to US preferred-partner infrastructure.",
      "impact": "This matters because rights language only changes bargaining power when it is backed by inspection, territorial reach, substitutable infrastructure, and a settled path for sharing upside."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "US vs EU",
    "ids": [
      "usa",
      "eu"
    ],
    "desc": "The defining regulatory divergence: permissive/default versus governed/extraterritorial.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Permission",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Default exclusion versus conditional access",
        "commentary": "The US stance excludes permission from the core training decision, while the EU requires conditional access. That is the central legal divergence: one treats use as defaultable, the other as governed."
      },
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Opacity versus observability",
        "commentary": "US opacity makes compliance hard to verify after data enters the system. EU observability creates a path for rights, provenance, and enforcement to be checked against actual system behavior."
      },
      {
        "row": "Provenance",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Scraped versus licensed corpus",
        "commentary": "The US model relies on scraped material, while the EU model uses licensed data. The comparison turns on whether training inputs are treated as available raw material or as governed supply."
      },
      {
        "row": "Territory",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Domestic market versus external reach",
        "commentary": "The US posture is domestic, but the EU is extraterritorial. That means EU governance can attach to foreign providers seeking access, while the US relies more on home-market defaults."
      },
      {
        "row": "Cloud Dependency",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "Provider lock-in versus portability",
        "commentary": "US preferred-partner dependency strengthens the incumbent platform, while EU portability supports substitution. This infrastructure row explains why regulatory rights may or may not translate into bargaining power."
      },
      {
        "row": "Output Allocation",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Who keeps the product",
        "commentary": "US output is retained, while EU output is shared. The value layer mirrors the legal layer: permissive use concentrates gains, conditional governance creates a negotiated allocation channel."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "Both stances govern frontier, multi-domain hosted systems that turn inputs into derived outputs through cloud deployment.",
      "different": "The US stack combines excluded permission, opaque audit, scraped corpus, domestic reach, preferred-partner cloud, and retained output, while the EU stack uses conditional permission, observable audit, licensed corpus, extraterritorial reach, portability, and shared output.",
      "impact": "The comparison shows that EU-style governance can convert rights into enforceable bargaining power, whereas the US default concentrates verification, infrastructure, and product value with the processor."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "US vs UK",
    "ids": [
      "usa",
      "uk"
    ],
    "desc": "UK rights posture diverges from US, but system and exit architecture often remain closer to US defaults.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Regulatory Posture",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Opposite copyright posture",
        "commentary": "The US is permissive and the UK is prohibitive. This is the clearest divergence: the UK protects rights holders more strongly at the legal threshold."
      },
      {
        "row": "Provenance",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Scraped versus licensed inputs",
        "commentary": "The US stance uses scraped data, while the UK requires licensed data. The UK therefore rejects the US default at the input layer even when other system choices remain similar."
      },
      {
        "row": "Cloud Dependency",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Same preferred-partner cloud shape",
        "commentary": "Both models depend on preferred cloud partners. The UK legal stance does not by itself create a more portable or sovereign infrastructure base."
      },
      {
        "row": "Model Sourcing",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Single-provider dependence persists",
        "commentary": "Both the US and UK are single-provider in this comparison. That keeps bargaining and operational control concentrated despite the UK taking a more restrictive rights position."
      },
      {
        "row": "Exit",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Exit remains entangled",
        "commentary": "Both sides end in entangled exit. This is the core UK tension: stronger rights language does not fully unwind dependency once systems, memory, and workflows are embedded."
      },
      {
        "row": "Output Allocation",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "Rights gap after licensing",
        "commentary": "The US allocates derived data rights, while the UK leaves them unallocated. The UK may protect the initial corpus more firmly but still leave downstream derived assets unsettled."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "Both the US and UK remain single-provider, preferred-partner cloud models with entangled exit despite different legal thresholds.",
      "different": "The UK rejects the US permissive scraped-input default through prohibitive licensing, but it still leaves derived data rights unallocated and does not solve infrastructure dependency or exit.",
      "impact": "The comparison matters because stronger input rights can still fail to restore leverage once downstream assets, provider control, and embedded workflows remain locked in."
    }
  },
