  },
  {
    "label": "Custody core",
    "ids": [
      "land-grab",
      "termination-trap",
      "rag",
      "custody-confidential-compute"
    ],
    "desc": "Custody wins when rights are weak; architecture determines whether custody and rights stay aligned.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Processing Mode",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Training creates the persistence gap",
        "commentary": "Status quo and termination-gap cases use training, while RAG and confidential compute use inference. That switch is the core custody move because inference can be disconnected without embedding source material into weights."
      },
      {
        "row": "Retention / Persistence",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Weight entanglement versus ephemerality",
        "commentary": "Weight-entangled systems preserve effects after the data relationship changes, while ephemeral designs keep use session-bound. Custody improves when the architecture prevents durable technical residue."
      },
      {
        "row": "Exit",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Exit depends on architecture",
        "commentary": "The status quo and termination gap are entangled, but RAG and confidential compute are clean. The same legal right has very different force depending on whether the system can actually be unwound."
      },
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "From opaque to observable",
        "commentary": "The sequence moves from opaque control to declared and then observable control. That progression shows why custody is not just possession of data; it is inspectable control over how the data is used."
      },
      {
        "row": "Derivation",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "Surviving capability defeats termination",
        "commentary": "The termination gap explicitly leaves surviving capability, while RAG leaves none. This row captures the legal failure mode: termination can be formally available but practically incomplete."
      },
      {
        "row": "Boundary",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Isolation hardens custody",
        "commentary": "Shared boundaries dominate the weaker custody cases, while confidential compute uses an isolated boundary. Isolation turns custody from a contractual promise into a system property."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "All custody cases involve governed data use where legal permission alone must be tested against how the system processes, retains, and exposes the data.",
      "different": "Training and weight entanglement in the status quo and termination gap leave opaque or surviving capability, while RAG and confidential compute move use toward inference, ephemerality, clean exit, stronger audit, and isolation.",
      "impact": "The comparison matters because termination and custody rights have practical force only when the architecture prevents durable residue and makes control inspectable."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "Exhaust lifecycle",
