        "row": "Access Control",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Custody depends on the control primitive",
        "commentary": "Key custody uses multi-key signoff, interception relies on ordinary API-style access, and confidential compute narrows authority through least privilege. The practical holder is the actor who can cause the system to act, not necessarily the named custodian."
      },
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "Visibility separates custody from access",
        "commentary": "The interception pattern is opaque while the other two are observable or declared. That makes nominal custody fragile: access can exist without an auditable custody relationship."
      },
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Audit rights only matter if they reach the access path",
        "commentary": "Declared audit rights fit key custody and nominal custody on paper, but confidential compute moves toward observable control. The comparison turns on whether audit attaches to the real execution channel."
      },
      {
        "row": "Model-Weight Rights",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Hosted-only rights do not settle control",
        "commentary": "All three keep weights hosted, but hosted-only transfer does not answer who can use, inspect, or interrupt the system. The custody question sits below formal transfer rights."
      },
      {
        "row": "Exit",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "Clean exit can mask residual access",
        "commentary": "Each stance presents clean or controlled reversibility, yet interception shows why exit from the nominal provider may not remove practical access. Reversibility is only clean if hidden channels are also removed."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "All three keep weights hosted and present controlled reversibility, so formal custody never becomes outright transfer.",
      "different": "The control primitive differs: multi-key custody and confidential compute expose auditable control paths, while interception leaves practical API-style access opaque to the named custodian.",
      "impact": "The comparison matters because custody is only real if audit, exit, and shutdown rights reach the actor who can actually cause the system to act."
    }
  },
