      {
        "row": "Model Sourcing",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Multi-provider routing versus single-provider depth",
        "commentary": "Apple uses multi-provider sourcing to keep frontier models as extensions to the product. OpenAI/Microsoft is single-provider, while Google can orchestrate in-house models around its own stack."
      },
      {
        "row": "Cloud Dependency",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "Dependence moves between cloud and platform",
        "commentary": "Apple is portable at the cloud layer but deeply controls the device and OS layer. Google is captive to its own cloud stack, while OpenAI/Microsoft sits in preferred-partner territory."
      },
      {
        "row": "Vertical Integration",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Control lives at different stack depths",
        "commentary": "Apple is stack-integrated around product experience, while Google is full-stack around compute infrastructure. OpenAI/Microsoft lacks the same platform default and instead depends on the partner contract and API distribution."
      },
      {
        "row": "Distribution Channel",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Default placement changes bargaining power",
