  {
    "label": "Legislating the gap",
    "ids": [
      "lord-holmes-ai-bill",
      "uk",
      "eu",
      "exhaust-derived-leverage"
    ],
    "desc": "Holmes's bill bridges the UK status quo and EU governance model, directly addressing the creative exhaust extraction that the UK's voluntary approach leaves unchecked.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "From declared to auditable",
        "commentary": "The UK relies on declared observability; Holmes's bill upgrades to auditable through accredited third-party audit, matching the EU. The exhaust stance stays at declared. This is the enforcement gap the bill closes: rights language without inspection changes nothing."
      },
      {
        "row": "Derived Value Capture",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Processor capture versus revenue share",
        "commentary": "The UK and the exhaust pattern both sit at processor captures — the status quo that Holmes's creative-industries advocacy targets. His bill and the EU both move to revenue share. The bill is the legislative mechanism for converting extraction into participation."
      },
      {
        "row": "Acceptance Basis",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Process legitimacy becomes mandatory",
        "commentary": "The UK accepts AI on a hybrid basis; the exhaust pattern operates on outcome-sufficient acceptance. Holmes's bill demands process-required legitimacy matching the EU. This is the bill's sharpest philosophical break: outcomes alone cannot justify deployment."
      },
      {
        "row": "Exit",
        "type": "tension",
        "title": "Entanglement persists across all governance models",
        "commentary": "The UK and Holmes both pick capability entangled. The exhaust stance sits at derived artifacts survive. Only the EU claims exportable exit. Holmes's solution is consent before ingestion rather than extraction after training. The entanglement problem survives even the strongest domestic governance framework."
      },
      {
        "row": "Nonproliferation Regime",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "From norms to enforcement",
        "commentary": "The UK relies on voluntary norms; the exhaust pattern has no regime at all. Holmes's bill creates an enforced domestic regime matching the EU. The shift from voluntary to statutory is the bill's central institutional innovation — offences, fines, and accredited audit replace good-faith cooperation."
      },
      {
        "row": "Tradeoff Authority",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Who decides speed versus safety",
        "commentary": "The exhaust pattern leaves tradeoff authority with product teams. The UK's safety body is advisory. Holmes's bill makes the AI Authority a statutory tradeoff body matching the EU's enforced standard. The bill transfers consequential authority from deployers to a public institution."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "All four profile frontier, general-purpose AI operating through informational channels. The capability object is the same — the split is about who governs, who captures value, and what evidence is required.",
      "different": "The UK relies on voluntary norms and declared observability with processor-captured value. The EU enforces statutory principles with auditable evidence, extraterritorial reach, and revenue sharing. Holmes codifies EU-style governance within UK domestic scope. The exhaust pattern operates in the permissive space that the UK status quo allows — outcome-sufficient, processor-captured, no regime.",
      "impact": "Holmes's bill would close the enforcement gap between UK rights language and practical governance, convert processor-captures extraction into revenue sharing, and make process legitimacy mandatory. But it cannot solve capability entanglement, which remains the structural exit problem that no jurisdiction has resolved."
