  {
    "label": "Output outruns oversight",
    "ids": [
      "ai-slop",
      "output-competence-schism",
      "audit-illusion",
      "saasapocalypse"
    ],
    "desc": "Four arrangements where AI-generated output exceeds the capacity of existing verification mechanisms. The spectrum runs from no oversight at all through nominal governance to structured testing, but none achieve verified quality at the point of use.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Opaque to declared — but never verified",
        "commentary": "Slop and the competence schism are fully opaque: consumers and organisations cannot tell the output was AI-generated or whether the producer understood it. The verification gap and the SaaSapocalypse move to declared observability, but declared is not verified. The full four-stance spectrum never reaches independently verifiable. Each step from opaque to declared adds paperwork without adding evidence."
      },
      {
        "row": "Evaluation",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Three evaluation levels, none sufficient",
        "commentary": "Slop and the competence schism are untested — output goes directly from generation to publication or deployment. The SaaSapocalypse runs internal tests. The verification gap has benchmarks. Even benchmarked evaluation does not prove fitness for the specific domain or context. The evaluation gap widens at every level because volume grows faster than review capacity."
      },
      {
        "row": "Containment",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "From no boundary to sandboxed",
        "commentary": "Slop and the competence schism have no containment: output flows freely from generation to the open web or organisational workflow. The verification gap has policy-only containment — governance without technical enforcement. Only the SaaSapocalypse provides sandboxed execution within defined workflow boundaries. The progression shows that meaningful containment requires technical barriers, not just rules."
      },
      {
        "row": "Acceptance Basis",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "What counts as good enough",
        "commentary": "Slop is market-validated: if it gets traffic, it is accepted. The competence schism and SaaSapocalypse are outcome-sufficient: if the output looks right, nobody asks how it was produced. The verification gap demands process — but the process is procedural when observability is only declared. Each acceptance basis creates a different quality gap, and none close it."
      },
      {
        "row": "Capability Limitation",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Safety filters do not filter for quality",
        "commentary": "Slop and the competence schism face no capability limitation at all: the models will produce mediocre articles and domain-crossing work without restriction. The SaaSapocalypse and verification gap have policy filters, but these restrict harmful content, not low-quality or incompetent content. The gap between safety alignment and quality assurance is where all four phenomena operate."
        },
      {
        "row": "Exit",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Clean exit does not mean clean consequences",
        "commentary": "Slop and the SaaSapocalypse have clean exit: the production relationship dissolves without residue. But slop's published content persists on the web, contaminating search and training data. The competence schism and verification gap leave derived artifacts: wrong architectures, inflated documentation, and institutionalised misattribution survive after the AI tool is gone."
      }
    ],
    "analysis": {
      "same": "All four describe civilian, informational, tool-grade AI output operating under broad permission and permissive regulation, where the verification mechanisms available to consumers, organisations, or regulators are structurally insufficient to distinguish quality from volume.",
      "different": "Slop and the competence schism are the unverified extremes — opaque, untested, uncontained, with no capability limitation. The SaaSapocalypse adds structured oversight through internal testing, sandboxing, and declared observability. The verification gap sits between: governance exists but fails to bind because declared observability substitutes for technical proof.",
      "impact": "The comparison reveals that the output-verification gap is not solved by adding governance layers. Moving from no oversight to policy to benchmarking to internal testing reduces risk incrementally but never closes the gap, because volume grows faster than review capacity and declared evidence is not the same as verified evidence."
    }
  },
  {
    "label": "The alignment problem at two scales",
    "ids": [
      "output-competence-schism",
      "agi-project"
    ],
    "desc": "Both are decoupling problems — evaluator less capable than the system — but at tool-grade the gap is ignored, and at superhuman the gap is existential.",
    "annotations": [
      {
        "row": "Domain Breadth",
        "type": "match",
        "title": "Same enabling property",
        "commentary": "General domain breadth is the structural root of both. At tool-grade it lets individuals produce across disciplines they cannot evaluate. At superhuman it makes containment to any single domain impossible. The cross-domain reach that creates office-level competence theatre is the same property that makes AGI ungovernable."
      },
      {
        "row": "Capability Class",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Scale of the decoupling",
        "commentary": "Tool-grade decouples individual workers from their output quality — the novice produces senior-looking work. Superhuman decouples entire institutions — even domain experts cannot evaluate the output. The schism is where the competence gap opens. The AGI project is where it becomes total."
      },
      {
        "row": "Observability",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Opposite institutional responses",
        "commentary": "The schism is opaque and nobody is trying to fix it — the output does not betray the novice and institutions reward the appearance. The AGI project demands independent verifiability because the stakes force the issue. Same structural problem, opposite response. The question is what level of catastrophe it takes to move from one posture to the other."
      },
      {
        "row": "Autonomy",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "The hollow loop versus no loop",
        "commentary": "The schism maintains human-in-loop supervision that does not work because the human cannot evaluate what passes through. The AGI project removes the human entirely with long-horizon autonomy. One is a pretence of oversight; the other is the honest abandonment of it. The schism is arguably less safe because the fiction of human review prevents anyone from building a real alternative."
      },
      {
        "row": "Evaluation",
        "type": "difference",
        "title": "Who checks the work",
        "commentary": "The schism is untested — no process asks whether the producer understands what they shipped. The AGI project demands certified decision-grade evaluation from independent parties. The distance between these two postures is the governance gap between where workplace AI use actually is and where it would need to be for the output to be trusted."
      }
    ]
  }
]
